<DocsLayout title="CLI Reference" description="LeanCTX v2.1.0 command-line interface — MCP server, shell hook, CLI commands, and persistent stats.">
  <p>
    LeanCTX is a single Rust binary that operates in multiple modes depending on the command-line arguments.
    It includes a full set of CLI commands alongside the MCP server and shell hook.
  </p>

  <h2>Installation</h2>

  <h3>Homebrew (macOS / Linux)</h3>
  <pre><code>brew tap yvgude/lean-ctx
brew install lean-ctx</code></pre>

  <h3>Windows</h3>
  <p>Download <code>lean-ctx-x86_64-pc-windows-msvc.zip</code> from <a href="https://github.com/yvgude/lean-ctx/releases/latest">GitHub Releases</a>, extract, and add to PATH. Or:</p>
  <pre><code>cargo install lean-ctx</code></pre>

  <h3>Cargo (all platforms)</h3>
  <pre><code>cargo install lean-ctx</code></pre>

  <h2>Usage</h2>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx [command] [options]</code></pre>

  <h2>Commands</h2>

  <h3>MCP Server (default, no args)</h3>
  <p>Starts the MCP server via stdio. This is the mode used by editors like Cursor, Claude Code, Copilot, Windsurf, OpenAI Codex, and Google Antigravity.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx</code></pre>

  <h3>init</h3>
  <p>Initialize LeanCTX for the current project or globally. With <code>--global</code>, auto-installs 23 shell aliases/functions into your shell profile (<code>.zshrc</code> / <code>.bashrc</code> on macOS/Linux, PowerShell profile on Windows).</p>
  <pre><code># Project-local setup
lean-ctx init

# Global shell alias installation (23 aliases)
lean-ctx init --global</code></pre>

  <h3>gain</h3>
  <p>
    Shows a <strong>visual terminal dashboard</strong> of your cumulative token savings across all sessions (MCP tools + shell hook).
    Features <strong>ANSI colors</strong>, Unicode block-chart bars, sparkline trends, color-coded compression rates, and USD cost estimates.
    Stats are stored in <code>~/.lean-ctx/stats.json</code>.
  </p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx gain                  # Visual dashboard
lean-ctx gain --graph          # Savings chart (last 30 days)
lean-ctx gain --daily          # Day-by-day breakdown table
lean-ctx gain --json           # Raw JSON export</code></pre>

