  <h3>dashboard</h3>
  <p>Opens a web dashboard at <code>http://localhost:3333</code> with interactive charts, KPI cards, and detailed breakdowns of MCP vs Shell Hook usage.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx dashboard
lean-ctx dashboard --port=8080</code></pre>

  <h3>discover</h3>
  <p>Analyzes your shell history and identifies commands that could be compressed by LeanCTX but are not currently using the shell hook.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx discover</code></pre>

  <h3>doctor</h3>
  <p>
    Runs 8 installation and environment diagnostics. Use after upgrades or when debugging MCP or shell-hook issues.
  </p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx doctor</code></pre>
  <p>Checks performed:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>PATH</strong> — <code>lean-ctx</code> binary found in system PATH</li>
    <li><strong>Version</strong> — binary version matches expected</li>
    <li><strong>Data directory</strong> — <code>~/.lean-ctx/</code> exists</li>
    <li><strong>Stats file</strong> — <code>~/.lean-ctx/stats.json</code> present</li>
    <li><strong>Config file</strong> — <code>~/.lean-ctx/config.toml</code> (optional, defaults used if absent)</li>
    <li><strong>Shell aliases</strong> — lean-ctx found in <code>.zshrc</code> / <code>.bashrc</code> / PowerShell profile</li>
    <li><strong>MCP config</strong> — <code>~/.cursor/mcp.json</code> contains lean-ctx</li>
    <li><strong>Dashboard port</strong> — port 3333 available for the web dashboard</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>tee</h3>
  <p>
    Manage error output logs stored in <code>~/.lean-ctx/tee/</code>. When <code>tee_on_error</code> is enabled,
    failed commands save their full output for debugging. All saved logs are automatically
    <strong>redacted</strong> (API keys, tokens, passwords, AWS keys, private keys are masked) and
    <strong>auto-deleted after 24 hours</strong>.
  </p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx tee list              # List all saved logs
lean-ctx tee clear             # Delete all logs
lean-ctx tee show &lt;filename&gt;   # View a specific log</code></pre>
  <p>
    <strong>Note:</strong> <code>tee_on_error</code> is <strong>disabled by default</strong> since v1.8.2.
    Enable with <code>lean-ctx config set tee_on_error true</code> if you want error output logging.
  </p>

  <h3>session</h3>
  <p>Shows adoption statistics — how many of your commands are using LeanCTX compression.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx session</code></pre>

  <h3>config</h3>
  <p>Manage the LeanCTX configuration file at <code>~/.lean-ctx/config.toml</code>.</p>
  <pre><code># Show current configuration
lean-ctx config

# Create default config file
lean-ctx config init

# Set a config value
lean-ctx config set ultra_compact true
lean-ctx config set checkpoint_interval 15
lean-ctx config set tee_on_error false</code></pre>

  <h3>read</h3>
  <p>Read a file with LeanCTX compression directly from the terminal.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx read src/auth.ts
lean-ctx read src/auth.ts --mode map
lean-ctx read src/auth.ts --mode signatures</code></pre>

  <h3>diff</h3>
  <p>Compare two files and show a compressed diff.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx diff src/auth.ts src/auth.backup.ts</code></pre>

  <h3>grep</h3>
  <p>Compressed grep — searches for patterns and returns compact results.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx grep "createUser" src/</code></pre>

  <h3>find</h3>
  <p>Compressed find — locates files with token-efficient output.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx find "*.ts" src/</code></pre>

  <h3>ls</h3>
  <p>Compressed directory listing with indentation-based format.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx ls src/</code></pre>

  <h3>deps</h3>
  <p>Shows the dependency graph for a file — imports, exports, and connections.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx deps src/auth.ts</code></pre>

  <h3>Shell Hook: -c / exec</h3>
  <p>Execute a command and compress the output before printing.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx -c git status
lean-ctx exec cargo build</code></pre>
  <p>Ideal for shell aliases (or use <code>lean-ctx init --global</code> to auto-install 23 of them):</p>
  <pre><code># Bash / Zsh (macOS / Linux)
alias git='lean-ctx -c git'
alias cargo='lean-ctx -c cargo'</code></pre>
  <p>On Windows (PowerShell):</p>
  <pre><code>{`function git { & lean-ctx -c "git $($args -join ' ')" }`}</code></pre>

  <h3>shell</h3>
  <p>Launch a shell wrapper that compresses all command output:</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx shell</code></pre>

  <h3>--version</h3>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx --version
# lean-ctx 2.1.0</code></pre>

  <h3>--help</h3>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx --help</code></pre>

